Now we show you how to belay your climbing partner in top rope climbing. Depending on the situation and your own preference, there are two different ways of holding the rope when belaying. First, the belaying hand above. This method is particularly suitable for beginners. The belaying hand is above the guide hand in the braking position. That is, in the event of a fall, the belaying hand pulls the rope down and thus tightens the HMS. In the second method, the belaying hand is below. This is mainly used when belaying the follower. If the climber falls, the guide hand pulls the rope in and the HMS locks automatically. The belaying hand guides the rope downwards out of the device. This makes it easier to give rope and take in rope slack.

To isolate the front wheel lift, I had the riders practice approaching a small obstacle and lifting the front wheel over it, but without hopping the back wheel. It's extremely important to keep your weight low and centered as you approach the obstacle. If you lean back at all when you lift the front wheel, the rear wheel is going to want to come up too soon. Instead, you really want to push the bars forward as you lift them. Once you feel comfortable lifting the front wheel over the obstacle, you can then practice the rear wheel lift. You want to think about bringing your feet up towards your butt. A lot of people make the mistake of trying to jump by pushing down on the pedals and then pulling up on the bars. Not only does this take more effort, but it makes it much harder to control your bike. This is a very natural motion that should feel similar to jumping up off the ground. Notice that this time the bike is more level. That's because we are pulling the bike up and not trying to jump off of it. Once you feel comfortable with both of these techniques you can then combine them together.

Okay, let's talk about contact point. So many players, they make their backswing, they start their forward swing, and then they look up to see where they hit the ball. Well, that's not a good idea because your head moves, your eyes move, and therefore your body moves and you lose your contact point. So what we want to do is pick out a contact point and you've heard it a million times, watch the ball. But specifically what do we watch on the ball? We want to watch the manufacturer's logo. There's a little logo on every tennis ball. That's your target, right there. Watch the manufacturer's logo as you make contact, and try to make contact out in front of your body. Now, that distance is going to vary. Obviously if I'm hitting a really high ball above my shoulder, my contact point is going to be more in front. If I have a really low ball, my contact point's going to be a little closer. But the key is, watch that manufacturer's logo and make contact out in front. Alright? So we've got two tips now: the racket low, contact out in front, and watch the logo. Now, a lot of players, they get confused, they say, well how come on TV I see the pros, they hit the ball way out in front?  Well, the reason why they're doing that is because they're hitting the ball on the rise as it's coming up. So their contact point is further out in front, which gives them more power. Now that's something that you could work on. Maybe as you get more advanced, you can start taking the ball a little earlier, but for beginners and intermediate players, I would suggest contacting the ball, you know, just after the peak of the bounce out in front.

It has to be a push. So I'm going to demonstrate a couple ways of teaching the horse to stop. This particular horse has a really good walk-halt transition. So it's fairly easy for me to stop him. He's a very responsive horse. And some horses find this very easy. Other horses find it much more difficult. If your horse finds it very difficult, it might take you a lot longer than the average training ride to teach your horse to stop. So I'm going to demonstrate on him. Good boy, good boy. You're doing great. Good boy. Again, I'm going to push him into the halt. Good boy. Good boy. I use my voice extensively. I think it's important to reward your horse, especially when they're learning something new. That was really good. Now, how does that translate into self-carriage? If I have a horse in a training level frame, in a long and low frame, in a medium level frame, or in a collected frame, in any frame at all, and I push him to the halt like that, and he stays in that frame to the halt, then I've achieved what I want. I haven't pulled him to the halt. I haven't restricted him to the halt. I've pushed him to the halt. And that's the essence of self-carriage. So, once you've taught your horse to do that from the walk, which can take quite a long time, and can be very frustrating, then you move it into the trot. Now I'm not going to do that with him. I wouldn't do that with him on a regular basis because this is not my horse. It's important for me to ride somebody else's horse as if it's somebody else's horse. Because I want the training that I'm doing to be very specific. So that every single thing I do on a daily basis with him is building to that self-carriage. So, if I get on him tomorrow, and he can stop a little bit better from the walk, then I might try it once from the trot. But I'm not going to drill and drill and drill and drill and drill, because all I'm going to do is create tension if he doesn't understand the question. So I hope those few tips will help you to understand what I mean by moving a beginning level horse or rider into a medium level horse or rider, which obviously is preparing them for the advanced level, and also the FEI levels. Thank you for watching.

Alright folks, today we're diving deep into the quirky world of tennis serves with something called the "Drunken" Serve. Now, don't let the name fool you; this isn't about serving after a few too many energy drinks. This is about a relaxed, loosey-goosey approach to the serve that can actually add some serious power and unpredictability to your game.

Our player here is showcasing the essence of this technique. Notice how he's not wound up like a coiled spring.  Instead, he's starting with a relaxed grip and letting his arm hang freely. Think of it like a pendulum gathering momentum. 

The key here is in the toss and the swing. It's all about timing and using your body's natural rhythm. See how he's almost letting the ball drop lower than usual? That allows him to generate power from his legs and core as he explodes upwards into the serve.

This relaxed approach can be a real game-changer, especially if you're prone to overthinking your serve. It can help you loosen up, find your natural rhythm, and unleash a serve that's got a bit of that "I-woke-up-like-this" swagger. 

Of course, mastering this serve takes practice. It's all about finding that sweet spot between controlled chaos and consistent power. But hey, that's part of the fun of tennis, right? Experimenting, tweaking, and finding what works for you.

Coming out of the water, it's time to tackle the bike leg. This year's course featured a challenging 40 kilometer ride with rolling hills. As you can see, the cyclists are heading out onto the open road. This section looks relatively flat, allowing athletes to find their rhythm and settle into a good pace after the swim. The scenery is fantastic; lush greenery and glimpses of the lake offer a welcome distraction from the physical exertion. Notice the cyclist up ahead, passing the traffic cone – that marks the turnaround point, meaning they're already halfway through this leg of the race. 

Now the course transitions away from the lakeshore and heads inland. This section of the bike course is known for some testing climbs. Looking at the elevation chart, you can see the infamous Lees Road climb coming up around the 5 kilometer mark – a 2 kilometer ascent with grades reaching 7 to 13%. It's a true test of endurance and strength. Then, after a brief respite, athletes face another climb as they navigate Northmount Road with its daunting 16% grade. This challenging terrain will really separate the strong riders from the pack.  But the reward for conquering these hills comes after the 16 kilometer mark, where the course transitions to a largely downhill run on Four Mile Lake Road. This is a chance to recover and gain some speed heading into the final transition.

Conversely, if you feel you're rocking in your hips, or one side is dipping, your saddle is probably a bit too low, so try raising it slightly. Also, think about what your body's doing whilst you're climbing. You don't want to be too rigid. Allow your hips to sway slightly with each pedal stroke and let your bike find its own way. This will feel strange at first, but with a bit of practice, it'll feel natural, and you'll be climbing much more efficiently as a result. When climbing out of the saddle, you recruit a larger muscle group to aid the effort and increase power. As you stand, shift your body weight slightly forward, almost over your handlebars. This will stop the rear wheel spinning out and help you to maintain traction. Keep pedalling smoothly whilst maintaining a steady cadence. Try to keep the bike as straight as possible. Avoid rocking it from side to side, as this is inefficient and a waste of energy. It can also be dangerous if you're in close proximity to other riders. When approaching a descent, shift up through the gears into a larger one. Stay relaxed and grip the handlebars lightly in the drops to maintain a lower centre of gravity, giving you greater control of the bike. By following these simple, straightforward techniques, you'll be amazed at how much more efficiently you'll climb, which after all is a battle against gravity. Ride smart and choose your moments to attack.

So when we ski and we start to make this turn, we realize we need a way to finish that turn.  And the way we finish that turn is that we let the skis come closer together. The mistake a lot of people make is they keep their feet shoulder width apart, and the skis run away from them. As they gain speed, they can't control their skis. So we want to learn how to control that speed, and by doing that, we learn how to bring our skis back together. That's one of the reasons that skiing is more difficult at slower speeds because you don't have the centrifugal force to help you make that turn.  So the goal is to keep your skis underneath you, stay balanced over your skis, and that's what helps you become a better skier.

Okay. So you're inside control and you're looking to attack. A common defense is for your opponent to keep their elbows tight to their ribs, making it difficult to separate the elbow for attacks like knee on belly or to sneak your arm in for submissions. Now, instead of getting frustrated and resorting to north-south, try this: place your bicep on their opposite elbow. This creates a small gap that you can exploit. If they try to drop their elbow or flatten out, put weight on their shoulder to force their back up, which in turn lifts their elbow. Now you can slide your arm in deeper and walk your hands towards their head, further exposing the arm. You can then lock your hands behind their head and use your belly to pull their other elbow up, giving you control of both arms. From here, you have options: attack either arm with a submission, transition to a more dominant position, or go for the choke. Remember, patience and pressure are key to breaking down their defense and opening up opportunities for attack.

Alright, let's move on to the next exercise. Mo's using a Swiss ball here, a fantastic tool for core stability. He's lying on it with his stomach and chest on the ball, legs extended back, toes on the ground for balance. Look at the control he has, keeping his body in a straight line. Now, he's going for the Swiss ball opposite arm and leg lift. Lifting one arm straight out and the opposite leg simultaneously, this is serious core engagement! This move is all about control and balance, working those deep stabilizing muscles that are crucial for runners. He's doing five reps, nice and slow, focusing on that mind-muscle connection. Remember, it's not about speed, it's about precision and engaging those core muscles.  

Now he's transitioning, smoothly moving into the lower back extension, still on that Swiss ball. His upper body drapes over the ball, creating a gentle stretch in the back. Now, he's engaging his lower back and glutes, lifting his chest up, creating that extension. Again, five reps, controlled and deliberate.  This exercise is fantastic for strengthening the lower back, which can be a weak point for many runners. A strong lower back helps prevent injuries and improves running form. Mo's really emphasizing quality over quantity here, and that's something we can all learn from. He's focusing on the movement, making each rep count.

The advantage of holding the brake hand up is that you have a little bit more power when belaying. This variant is therefore more suitable for heavy climbers. The advantage of holding the handbrake down is that the movement is more ergonomic and the hand gets tired less quickly. This variant is therefore particularly suitable for long climbing routes. If the climber wants to climb up again, always make sure that the handbrake cable runs above the carabiner. This ensures that the belayer can react immediately in the event of a fall and can hold the climber.  In principle, both variants of holding the brake hand are safe, as long as the basic principles of belaying are observed. These are: the brake hand never leaves the brake cable, the belayer always pays attention to the climber, and the belayer reacts immediately to a fall.

Stage 4 starts in Mansfield and is one for the puncheurs, with over 1400m of climbing packed into its 175km. The stage heads north out of Mansfield before tackling eight climbs as it heads towards the finish in Newark-on-Trent. The hilliest section comes in the middle of the route, with four categorised climbs within 50km, and this is where the peloton could well be fractured. But with 40km from the final climb to the finish, it might be difficult for a breakaway to stay away. Stage 5 is a 16km out-and-back individual time trial on the east coast in Tendring, Essex, providing the last real opportunity for the GC contenders to gain time. It is mostly flat, with just 122m of elevation in total, so will be a fast and furious race against the clock that will be decided by the narrowest of margins. The winner of this stage has a strong chance to take home the overall. And finally, the overall winner will be crowned at the end of stage 8 on Sunday the 10th in Cardiff city centre.

Alright so she's got the breath, now I want you to think about bringing your upper chest to the bar. Yep. That's it. So you guys see how that elevates her a little bit more. You can even see a little bit more definition in her upper back because she's pulling that air in. That's good. Drive your feet, there you go. Now we're talking. Good, so she took two reps there.  Take one more. Keep your upper chest up. Yep. That's it, perfect. And rack it. So you guys can already see a major difference, and we've only addressed one thing, breathing. That's something as simple as a breathing cue, and she's already in a better position. So the other thing I want you guys to pay attention to is when she brings that bar down, the bar path isn't completely vertical, but it's not so far out in front that she's doing almost a decline press. We want her elbows stacked over her wrists, because what that's gonna do is it's gonna help her use more triceps, it's going to keep her tighter, and it's going to shorten that range of motion. So, Lily, we're going to do this from the top down. I want you to unrack the bar. I want you to bring the bar down and touch right about, yep, right about there. A little bit lower, there you go. Now keep your butt down and try to drive up. And you see how her butt came up. Good, and rack it. Now, that wasn't because of anything else other than her trying to find that stability. She's trying to find that leverage to drive the weight up. So, we're going to do the same thing, but when you unrack this time, Lily, and you bring the bar down to your chest, you're going to tuck your elbows in a little bit more. You're gonna bring your elbows in towards your sides, take that same breath into your upper chest, and then drive straight up. You ready? Yep. Unrack, big breath, tuck, yep, drive. There we go. Now, that was much better. We're going to take three more reps like that. That's it, good. One more. Big breath, tight, good. And rack it. So you guys see that when she brings her elbows in a little bit more, she stays much tighter. She's able to use her triceps, she's able to drive the weight, and she's not having to use her lower body to get that extra drive. And the biggest thing that I preach to my lifters is efficiency, because if you can't be efficient in this lift, in any lift, you're leaving pounds on the bar. So I hope that these two little cues for you long limb lifters out there really helps you benefit on your bench. This is something that I've had to struggle with my entire life. Being 5'8" with a 76-inch wingspan, it sucks, but there are ways around it. So again, this is Christian Anto with Elite FTS and Lily, and we will see you guys next time.

As your front end comes up, you need to simultaneously pull back and up with your arms, while keeping your legs relatively neutral. Some beginners will pull up on the bars, only to push them forward, which cancels out the upward motion. The goal is to get the bars as close to your waist as possible. You can even imagine trying to touch your chest to the stem of your handlebars. Once you get to this point, you're basically just coasting through the air.  The final part is bringing your knees up to level out the bike. This may happen naturally as you pull up with your arms. However, if you need to gain more height, this is where you can use your legs to help. The best part about riding in Miami is you can bunny hop your way right to the beach.

Now this 585, this felt great, you guys saw that bar speed, this was moving really well. So at this point, I knew 675 was there. I knew my previous PR was there. The question was, would 700 be there? And the answer to that question was, I had no idea. But we are going to find out together right now. Now, the opening pull to this 675 was brutal. My back was absolutely screaming at me at this point. And the funny thing is, when I watch this back, it doesn't even look that bad. It just looks like I'm setting up for a heavy deadlift. But I guarantee you, everything inside was screaming. 
Now, this 675 went up, in my opinion, slower than the 585. So the reality was setting in that 700 pounds was going to be a fight. But what I did have on my side, was that this 675 felt about the same as my previous PR of 690. So even though it went up a little bit slower, I still had that one rep max strength in the tank, because I was fresh, I paced myself very well and this was my moment. So we loaded up the 700 pounds and we're about to see history. I'm about to pull 700 pounds for the first time ever. So without further ado, let's get right into it. 
Now, as I approach the bar, I'm taking in the moment, I'm trying to remember everything my coach is telling me, keeping my lower back as flat as possible, ripping the bar off the ground, but most importantly, not dying. Now at this point in time, everything goes silent. Even though I'm in a gym full of my best friends, everything goes silent and it's just me versus the barbell. So I take in one last deep breath and we go for it. 
I don't even remember these next couple of seconds happening, it just happened so fast. All I remember is my friends erupting and going crazy as I dropped the weight, and in that moment, I knew that I had achieved something special. It wasn't pretty, by any stretch of the imagination, but it was a good pull, and I knew from that point on that the floodgates were open and I was well on my way to pulling even more. So there you have it, guys. That was my 700-pound deadlift, something that I'm very proud of. I know I can do better, I know I can do more, but in that moment, it was everything that I could ask for and more. So I really hope you guys enjoyed the video. If you did, be sure to smash that like button and we'll catch you in the next one. Peace out.

So we're going to talk about leg yielding today. I leg yield this horse in walk. I leg yield him in trot. And I'm going to leg yield him in canter in just a minute. It's a really, really good exercise to supple up the horse's body. For example, my horse is, I always say this, a little more difficult on the left rein. He doesn't bend as easily to the left. He's a little stiffer to the left. And the leg yield is a great exercise to make him supple. It also teaches the rider to separate their aids because when you're leg yielding, one leg has to be at the girth and the other one has to be behind the girth. So you're really asking the horse with one leg, you're pushing the horse over to the other rein and you're using your new outside rein to regulate the outside shoulder. And, of course, your seat bones are following the line that you're traveling on. So in that way, it's a great exercise for horse and rider.

Okay, so we've covered the importance of that low-to-high swing for net clearance and closing the racket face to avoid hitting long. Now for tip number three, this is a big one for consistency and control. We want to keep that racket face vertical throughout the entire contact area. It's not enough to just be vertical at the moment of impact. We want to maintain that vertical position as we're brushing up the back of the ball. 

Now, you might be thinking, "My arm doesn't move straight up and down, it swings in an arc." And you're absolutely right. But the key is, we're talking about the racket face itself remaining vertical, not necessarily your arm.  Think about it like this: imagine a line going straight up from the ground towards the sky. As you swing through the ball, you want the racket face to travel along that line, maintaining its vertical orientation even as your arm swings in its natural arc.

This might feel a bit strange at first, especially if you're used to rolling your wrist or making other adjustments during your swing. But trust me, keeping that racket face vertical through the contact zone will do wonders for your control and consistency. You'll find that you hit the ball with more power and accuracy, and you'll be much less likely to spray the ball around the court.

I'm going to be testing out this, the GoPro Max lens mod. This is GoPro's new lens that gives you that super wide, almost fisheye look. It's designed to work with their Hero 9 and Hero 10 cameras. Now, the lens is only compatible with the GoPro's "Max lens mode", which essentially crops in on the sensor a little bit to give you that hyper smooth stabilization. That means my racket has to get down to about knee level for a waist-high ball, okay? And my swing, you can see it's low to high. Now, a lot of players, particularly beginners and intermediate players, their swing is pretty good. They do get down low enough on that waist-high ball, but as soon as you ask them to hit a ball that's a little bit higher than waist high, maybe chest high, they don't make the adjustment, okay? They'll still go 12 inches below the contact point, but since the contact point is now chest high, their racket's only dropping down to about waist high and then they're swinging up and the ball goes into the net. So what you have to remember is this: Always go 12 inches, 1 foot below the anticipated contact point. So if the ball's coming to me chest high, I gotta get the racket down to about waist high, okay, before I swing up. That's what I call the drop.

Here we see the new laws in effect. Notice how the tackler, highlighted in the white circle, quickly releases the tackled player and gets to his feet. He's now eligible to contest for the ball, but only from behind his own side of the breakdown midpoint. The midpoint, remember, isn't defined by the ball itself but by where the players are in contact. 

See how the arriving players are respecting the offside line, which in this case, is the hindmost foot of the tackled player.  They're also staying on their feet and not using their hands on the ground. This creates a cleaner, more dynamic contest for possession.
